1 (8) a local conservation district;
2 (9) an organization that focuses on environmental or wildlife
3 protection or conservation;
4 (10) a local water management district;
5 (11) the Kansas agricultural banking or appraisal industry;
6 (12) a student at a state educational institution engaged in a course of
7 study related to water;
8 (13) a Kansas municipality;
9 (14) a provider of natural resources education;
10 (15) the Kansas agricultural commodity associations;
11 (16) the Kansas water authority or regional advisory committee;
12 (17) the Kansas livestock industry; or
13 (18) the Kansas grain and feed industry.
14 (c) (1) Members of the task force shall be residents of Kansas. The
15 task force shall consist of at least one member from each of the five
16 conservation regions of the state. Not more than two members of the task
17 force shall represent the same stakeholder enumerated in subsection (b).
18 (2) The speaker of the house of representatives and the president of
19 the senate shall ensure that the requirements of paragraph (1) are met.
20 (d) Members of the task force shall be appointed by April 30, 2025.
21 Any vacancy in the membership of the task force shall be filled by
22 appointment in the same manner prescribed by this section for the original
23 appointment.
24 (e) The speaker of the house of representatives shall select one
25 member of the task force who is a member of the house of representatives
26 to serve as co-chairperson of the task force. The president of the senate
27 shall select one member of the task force who is a member of the senate to
28 serve as co-chairperson of the task force.
29 (f) (1) The task force may meet at any time and at any place within
30 the state upon the call of either co-chairperson.
31 (2) A majority of voting members shall constitute a quorum of the
32 task force. All actions of the task force may be taken by a majority of
33 members present when there is a quorum.
34 (3) If approved by the legislative coordinating council, members of
35 the task force attending meetings authorized by the task force shall be paid
36 amounts for expenses, mileage and subsistence as provided in K.S.A. 75-
37 3223(e), and amendments thereto.
38 (4) The staff of the office of revisor of statutes, the legislative
39 research department and the division of legislative administrative services
40 shall provide such assistance as may be requested by the task force.
41 (g) The water program task force shall:
42 (1) Evaluate major risks to the quality and quantity of the state's
43 water supply, including any impact on current and future economic growth

S Sub HB 2172 3
1 and population stability;
2 (2) steps that the state must take to define and achieve a future supply
3 of water for Kansans; and
4 (3) evaluate current funding for water in the state and determine
5 whether such funding is sufficient to address the water issues included in
6 the state water plan, including the state's current and future water
7 infrastructure needs.
8 (h) The task force shall prepare and submit a report to the legislature
9 and the governor on or before January 31, 2026. Such report shall include
10 recommendations on:
11 (1) The water program's long-term structure to address the state's
12 current and future water needs, including, but not limited to:
13 (A) The roles and responsibilities of the state, municipalities and
14 regional entities;
15 (B) how the program's investments and successes should be
16 evaluated, including gathering any stakeholder input; and
17 (C) criteria to determine program investments, including geographic
18 diversity of such investments; and
19 (2) funding for the water program, including, but not limited to:
20 (A) New dedicated moneys or investments for the state water plan
21 fund;
22 (B) changes to any existing fees or moneys dedicated to the state
23 water plan fund; and
24 (C) any additional funding sources or tools necessary to ensure that
25 the financial resources are adequate to address the state's water issues.
26 (i) (1) On or before June 30, 2025, the co-chairs of the task force
27 shall jointly appoint five individuals to a water planning work group. Such
28 individuals may be members of the water program task force but are not
29 required to be members of the task force. The individuals shall be
30 attorneys, engineers, hydrologists, natural resource planners or others with
31 relevant experience with Kansas water issues.
32 (2) The work group shall meet regularly as may be necessary to
33 conduct a study of the state water resource planning act, K.S.A. 82a-901 et
34 seq., and amendments thereto, and develop draft legislation that proposes
35 modernization of such act. The work group shall work jointly with the task
36 force and consider recommendations made by the task force relating to
37 (A) How the state water plan is created;
38 (B) what the state water plan should prioritize;
39 (C) how the state water plan is implemented;
40 (D) how recommendations for state water plan appropriations are
41 made to the legislature;
42 (E) any future studies that might be undertaken; and
43 (F) any other related or relevant matters.

